<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<section xml:id="sec-SingleVariance" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Chi-Square test for Variance</title>
 
  <introduction>
    <p>
    In this section we will learn how to perform a chi-square test for variance and standard deviation. We will review using the chi-square distribution to test hypotheses about variance and standard deviation. We will also learn how to write the conclusion for the chi-square test in context.
    </p>
  </introduction>


<objectives>
  <introduction>
    <p> At the end of this section you will be able to:   </p>
  </introduction>
  <ol>
    <li> <p> Write hypotheses involving variance and standard deviation </p>    </li>
    <li> <p> Perform chi-square test for variance. </p> </li>
<li> <p> Perform chi-square test for standard deviation. </p> </li>
     <li> <p> Write the conclusion for chi-square test in context </p>    </li>
        </ol>
</objectives>

<subsection xml:id="subsec-ChiTestVarianceBasics">
  <title> Chi-Square Hypothesis Test </title>
<p>A one-sample <m>\chi ^2</m>-test for a population variance is used to test a claim about the variability of a quantitative population when the population is normally distributed. When the <term> hypothesize claim</term> refer to standard deviation we will use <m> \sigma</m> in the hypotheses  and when the hypothesized situation refers to the variance we will use <m> \sigma ^2</m> in the hypotheses. In this test, the sample variance <m>s^2</m> is compared to a hypothesized population variance <m>\sigma ^2</m> to determine whether the observed variability is significantly different from the claimed value. </p> 
<p> The <term> test statistic</term> is computed as <m>\chi^2=\dfrac{(n-1)s^2}{\sigma^2}</m>, where <m>n</m> is the sample size. When the population is normal, this test statistic follows a <term>chi-square distribution</term> with <m>n-1</m> degrees of freedom. We will use StatKey to calculate the p-values. The resulting <term>p-value</term> is then used to decide whether to reject the null hypothesis and conclude that the population variance differs from, is greater than, or is less than the hypothesized value. </p>

<definition xml:id="def-one-sample-chi-square-test-variance">
  <statement>
    <p>
      A <term>one-sample <m>\chi^2</m>-test for a population variance or standard deviation</term> is
      a statistical method used to test a claim about the variance or standard deviation of a normally distributed population. </p> 
      <p> The test statistic is <md>\chi^2=\dfrac{(n-1)s^2}{\sigma ^2}</md> where <m>s^2</m> is the sample variance, <m> \sigma ^2</m> is the population variance, <m>n</m> is the sample size, and with degrees of freedom <m> n-1.</m>
    </p>
  </statement>
</definition>

<p> When you are given the variance, the value is already squared. When you are given the standard deviation you need to remember to square the value. </p>

<p> review critical and p-values on StatKey </p>






  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-ChiTestVarianceExamples">
  <title>Examples of Chi-Squared Test </title>
    <p>
      A machine is designed to fill bags of flour so that the variability in bag
      weights have a population variance of <m>1.5</m> ounces squared. A quality
      control manager wants to test whether the true variance in bag weights is
      different from <m>1.5</m> ounces squared. A random sample of
      <m>20</m> bags is taken, and the sample variance is found to be
      <m>2.4</m> ounces squared. Test the claim at the
      <m>\alpha=0.05</m> significance level.    </p>

<example> <title>Flour Bags</title>
  <statement>
<p>
      State the null and alternative hypotheses, verify the conditions for a
      one-sample <m>\chi ^2</m>-test for variance, compute the test statistic,
      find the <em>p-value</em> with StatKey, and state your conclusion in context.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution> <title>Hypotheses</title>
    <p>   Let <m>\sigma^2</m> be the population variance in bag weights. </p>
<p>The hypotheses are
    <md> H_0:\sigma^2=1.5 \qquad H_a:\sigma^2\ne 1.5.     </md> </p>
</solution>
<solution> <title>Test Statistic</title>
    <p>
      Since this is a test about a single population variance, we use a
      one-sample <m>\chi^2</m>-test for variance. The test statistic is
       <md> \chi^2=\frac{(n-1)s^2}{\sigma_0^2} =\frac{(20-1)(2.4)}{1.5} =\frac{45.6}{1.5} =30.4.
    </md> </p> 
</solution>
<solution> <title>p-value</title>
    <p>  The degrees of freedom are   <m>df=n-1=20-1=19</m>.   </p>
    <p>  For a two-tailed test with <m>df=19</m>, change the middle area to 0.95 so the combined area of the tails is 0.05, thus the <term>critical values</term> are      approximately <m>\chi^2=8.907</m> and <m>\chi^2=32.852</m>. Since test value
      <m>30.4</m> is between these two critical values, the test statistic does
      not fall in the rejection region wo we will not reject the null hypothesis. </p>
<p> For the p-value click on <c>Two Tail</c> and enter the test value 30.4 on the right side, combine the tail area for <m>p-value = 2(0.047)=0.094 </m>. since the p-value is greater than <m> \alpha = 0.05</m> do not reject the null hypothesis. </p> 
    </solution>
<solution><title> Conclusion</title>
    <p>
      Therefore, we fail to reject <m>H_0</m>. At the <m>0.05</m> significance
      level, there is not enough evidence to conclude that the population
      variance in bag weights is different from <m>1.5</m> ounces squared.
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>

    <p>
      A biologist is studying the consistency of seed weights from a particular
      plant species grown in a laboratory. Under standard growing conditions, the
      population standard deviation of seed weights is believed to be
      <m>0.8</m> grams. The biologist wants to test whether the true population
      standard deviation has increased under a new nutrient treatment.
    </p>
    <p>
      A random sample of <m>25</m> seeds is collected, and the sample standard
      deviation is found to be <m>1.1</m> grams. At the <m>\alpha =0.05</m>
      significance level, test whether the population standard deviation has increased
      from <m>0.8</m> grams. Assume the population of seed weights is
      approximately normally distributed.
    </p>

<example> <title> Seedlings</title>
  <statement>
 <p> State the null and alternative hypotheses, verify the conditions for a
      one-sample <m>\chi ^2</m>-test for standard deviation, compute the test statistic,
      find the <em>p-value</em> with StatKey, and state your conclusion in context.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution> <title> Hypotheses</title>
    <p>
      Let <m>\sigma</m> be the population standard deviation of seed weights.
       <md> H_0:\sigma=0.8 \qquad H_a:\sigma\gt 0.8     </md>
Since the chi-square procedure is based on variance, we can write the
      hypotheses in terms of <m>\sigma^2</m>.
      Equivalently, these may be written as
        <md> H_0:\sigma^2=0.64 \qquad H_a:\sigma^2\gt 0.64.   </md>
This will be a right-tailed test. </p>
</solution>
<solution><title>Test Statistic</title>
    <p>
      The sample size is <m>n=25</m>, so the degrees of freedom are
      <m>df=n-1=24</m>. The sample standard deviation is <m>s=1.1</m>, so the
      sample variance is  <m>s^2=(1.1)^2=1.21   </m> </p>
    <p>  The test statistic is
        <md> \chi^2=\frac{(n-1)s^2}{\sigma_0^2} 
=\frac{(25-1)(1.21)}{0.64}
=\frac{24(1.21)}{0.64}
=\frac{29.04}{0.64}
=45.375.     </md>     </p>
</solution>
<solution> <title> p-value</title>
    <p>  For a right-tailed test with <m>df=24</m> and <m>\alpha=0.05</m>, the right <term>critical value</term> <m>\chi^2 =36.415</m>. The test value of 45.375 lands in the reject region so we will reject the null hypothesis. </p>
<p> For the <term>p-value</term> click on Right Tail and enter the test value 45.375 along the bottom to get the area of <m>p-value=0.0053</m>. Since the p-value is less than <m>\alpha=.05</m> we will reject the null hypothesis. 
    </p>
</solution>
<solution><title>Conclusion</title>
    <p>
      Since we rejected <m>H_0</m> at the <m>0.05</m> significance level,
      there is sufficient evidence to conclude that the population standard
      deviation of seed weights under the new nutrient treatment has increased
      <m>0.8</m> grams.
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>



  </subsection>

<subsection xml:id="subsec-ChiTestVariancePractice">
  <title>Practice Problems </title>

<exercise> <title> Rainfall</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      A climate scientist is studying the year-to-year variability in annual
      rainfall for a particular region. Historically, the population standard
      deviation of annual rainfall has been <m>3.2</m> inches. The scientist
      wants to test whether climate change has altered the variability in annual
      rainfall.
    </p>
    <p>
      A random sample of <m>18</m> recent years is selected, and the sample
      standard deviation of annual rainfall is found to be <m>4.5</m> inches.
      At the <m>0.05</m> significance level, test whether the population
      standard deviation differs from <m>3.2</m> inches. Assume the distribution
      of annual rainfall is approximately normal.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution><title> Hypotheses</title>
    <p>
      Let <m>\sigma</m> be the population standard deviation of annual rainfall.
      
    <md> H_0:\sigma=3.2 \qquad H_a:\sigma\ne 3.2     </md>
    Since the chi-square procedure is based on variance, we can also write the
      hypotheses in terms of variance:
    <md> H_0:\sigma^2=10.24 \qquad H_a:\sigma^2\ne 10.24.     </md>
This is a two-tailed test. </p>
</solution>
<solution> <title> Statistical Test</title>
    <p>
      The sample size is <m>n=18</m>, so the degrees of freedom are
      <m>df=n-1=17</m>. The sample standard deviation is <m>s=4.5</m>, so the
      sample variance is <m>s^2=(4.5)^2=20.25  </m>. </p>
<p> The test statistic is
        <md> \chi^2=\frac{(n-1)s^2}{\sigma_0^2}
=\frac{(18-1)(20.25)}{10.24}
=\frac{17(20.25)}{10.24}
=\frac{344.25}{10.24} \approx 33.62.     </md> </p>
</solution>
    <solution> <title> p-value</title>
<p>
      For a two-tailed test with <m>df=17</m> and <m>\alpha=0.05</m>, the
      critical values are a <m>\chi^2_L=7.564</m> and <m>\chi^2_R=30.191</m>.
      Since the test statistic <m>33.62</m> is greater than the upper critical
      value <m>30.19</m>, it falls in the rejection region and we reject the null hypothesis. </p>
<p> For the p-value click on Two Tails and enter the test value 33.62 on the right, the
   <m>p-value=2(0.0094)=0.0188</m> which is smaller than <m>\alpha = 0.05 </m> so we reject the null hypothesis. </p>
</solution>
<solution> <title> Conclusion</title>
    <p>
      Since we reject <m>H_0</m> at the <m>0.05</m> significance level,
      there is sufficient evidence to conclude that the population standard
      deviation of annual rainfall differs from <m>3.2</m> inches, suggesting
      that the variability in rainfall may have changed.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise> <title> Vapes</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      A public health researcher is studying the consistency of nicotine content
      in a particular brand of disposable vapes. The manufacturer claims that
      the population variance in nicotine content is <m>0.25</m>
      milligrams squared. The researcher wants to test whether the true variance
      differs from this claimed value.
    </p>
    <p>
      A random sample of <m>16</m> disposable vapes is selected, and the sample
      variance in nicotine content is found to be <m>0.49</m> milligrams
      squared. At the <m>0.05</m> significance level, test whether the
      population variance in nicotine content differs from <m>0.25</m>
      milligrams squared. Assume the nicotine content is approximately normally
      distributed.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution><title> Hypotheses</title>
    <p>
      Let <m>\sigma^2</m> be the population variance in nicotine content. The
      hypotheses are
        <md> H_0:\sigma^2=0.25 \qquad H_a:\sigma^2\ne 0.25.     </md>
This is a two-tailed test. </p>
</solution>
<solution> <title> Statistical Test</title>
    <p>
      The sample size is <m>n=16</m>, so the degrees of freedom are
      <m>df=n-1=15</m>. The sample variance is <m>s^2=0.49</m>.
    </p>
    <p> The test statistic is 
    <md> \chi^2=\frac{(n-1)s^2}{\sigma_0^2}
=\frac{(16-1)(0.49)}{0.25} =\frac{15(0.49)}{0.25} =\frac{7.35}{0.25} =29.4   </md></p>
</solution>
    <solution> <title> p-value</title>
<p>
      For a two-tailed test with <m>df=15</m> and <m>\alpha=0.05</m>, the
      critical values are   <m>\chi^2_L=6.262</m> and <m>\chi^2_R=27.489</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Since the test statistic <m>29.4</m> is greater than the upper critical
      value <m>27.49</m>, it falls in the rejection region and we reject the null hypothesis.
    </p>
<p> for the p-value click on Two Tails and enter the test value 29.4 along the bottom. The <m>p-value=2(0.014)=.028</m>. Since the p-value is less than <m>\alpha =0.05</m> we reject the null hypothesis. </p>
</solution>
<solution> <title> Conclusion</title>
    <p>
      Since we reject <m>H_0</m> at the <m>0.05</m> significance level,
      there is sufficient evidence to conclude that the population variance in
      nicotine content differs from <m>0.25</m> milligrams squared.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>



  </subsection>






  
</section>
